    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When calculating interest on your student loan each month, the lender calculates the interest accrued from the previous month's balance. The interest is typically calculated using a daily interest method, which assumes interest is charged daily. This means daily interest balances are calculated, and then divided by the number of days in the current month to determine the monthly interest. This daily calculation can make it seem like the principal is not decreasing, even if the monthly balance is the correct amount. This is why it may take several months to see a decrease in the principal balance.",
